Class PureIterable.Sized<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • fluent.ly.PureIterable.Sized<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - some arbitrary type
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    PureIterable<T>, java.lang.Iterable<T>
    Enclosing interface:
    PureIterable<T>
    public abstract static class PureIterable.Sized<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements PureIterable<T>
    A kind of PureIterable which provides an additional size() service.

    For the size service to be meaningful, there is an underlying contract arranging the mutual expectations between two parties: the customer, and the supplier. (Customers are clients of this class, a supplier is a non-abstract class which extends this class):

    1. The size of an instance is the number of elements it yields. It should be clear that the size can never be negative.
    2. The instance always returns the same number of items. Or, a bit more formally, all Iterator instances that method iterator() returns are exhausted after precisely the same number of calls to Iterator#hasNext()
    3. This fixed size can be computed efficiently, specifically without exhausting the sequence items that this iterable may yield.
    Since:
    2014-06-20
    Author:
    Yossi Gil
